(52, 1, '2018-09-17 09:53:10', '2018-09-17 16:53:10', 'The project emerged from Schafer\'s reaction to the increasing degradation of Vancouver\'s developing soundscape, as well as work as a professor atÂ <a title=\"Simon Fraser University\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Fraser_University\">Simon Fraser University</a>Â where he taught a course in noise pollution in attempt to draw attention to the sonic environment.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Soundscape_Project#cite_note-5\">[5]</a></sup>Â The project quickly attracted a small group of young composers and communications students, and after receiving support from theÂ <a class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Donner Canadian Foundation\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donner_Canadian_Foundation\">Donner Canadian Foundation</a>Â it began its first project in 1972: a detailed study of the soundscape ofÂ <a title=\"Vancouver\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vancouver\">Vancouver</a>. The study resulted in a recording,Â <i>The Vancouver Soundscape</i>Â which was published in 1973. It consisted ofÂ <a title=\"Field recording\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_recording\">phonographical</a>Â recordings of local soundscapes and soundmarks as well as a spoken documentary recording by R. Murray Schafer discussing notions of acoustic design, providing analysis of examples of good and bad acoustic design in Vancouver, illustrated with further recordings. This recording is notable for its phonographic approach and is distinct from later WSP recordings in that it features no on-site narration. However, some of the recordings do bear the beginnings of more compositional approaches to soundscape recording, evidenced particularly in the track, \'Entrance to the Harbour\' in which a 30-minute boat journey is condensed into a 7-minute montage in an effort to highlight the important sound events. The recordists of this publication were Howard Broomfield, Bruce Davis, Peter Huse and Colin Miles.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Soundscape_Project#cite_note-6\">[6]</a></sup>\r\n\r\nVisit <a title=\"Word Soundscape Project website\" href=\"https://www.sfu.ca/~truax/wsp.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">World Soundscape Project</a>\r\n\r\nhttp://www.sfu.ca/sonic-studio/excerpts/PacificFanfare.mp3\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'World Soundscape Project', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'world-soundscape-project', '', '', '2018-10-01 10:37:01', '2018-10-01 17:37:01', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?p=52', 3, 'post', '', 0),
